example.p:
Consider the function
f(x) = \begin{cases} x^2\sin\frac{1}{x} \amp\text{if }x\ne 0 \\ 0 \amp\text{if }x=0 \end{cases}
For x\ne 0 we have, by the product and chain rules,
f'(x) \amp= 2x\, \sin\frac{1}{x} + x^2 \left(\cos\frac{1}{x}\right) \left(-\frac{1}{x^2}\right)
\amp= 2x\, \sin\frac{1}{x} - \cos\frac{1}{x}
As \left|\sin\frac{1}{x}\right|\le 1, we have
\lim_{x\rightarrow 0}2x\, \sin\frac{1}{x}=0
On the other hand, as x tends to zero, \frac{1}{x} goes to \pm\infty. So
\lim_{x\rightarrow 0}\cos\frac{1}{x} = DNE \implies \lim_{x\rightarrow 0}f'(x) = DNE
We will now see that, despite this, f'(0) is perfectly well defined. By definition
f'(0) \amp= \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{f(h)-f(0)}{h}
\amp = \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{h^2\sin\frac{1}{h}-0}{h}
\amp = \lim_{h\to 0} h\sin\frac{1}{h}
\amp = 0\qquad\text{since }\left|\sin\frac{1}{h}\right|\le 1
So f'(0) exists, but is not equal to \lim_{x\rightarrow 0}f'(x), which does not exist.
